{
  "texts": [
    "Hyperspectral image reconstruction methods were initially very complex (Fu et al. 2021), but the advent of deep learning has opened new possibilities in this field (Ahmed et al. 2023b; Archana and Jeevaraj 2024).",
    "Algorithms now show impressive results in reconstructing hyperspectral images from even low-quality RGB inputs, effectively combining spatial clarity with essential spectral details (Xie et al. 2019; Qin et al. 2023).",
    "These advancements make hyperspectral data more accessible and easier to use, helping various sectors make more accurate decisions (Zhao et al. 2022; Cui et al. 2022; Deng et al. 2024).",
    "Deep learning's proficiency in parsing complex patterns in extensive datasets allows for superior-quality reconstructions from incomplete or noisy data (Tian et al. 2020; Wang et al. 2021b).",
    "However, transforming RGB to hyperspectral data is complex, as it involves reconstructing detailed spectral information from the limited data in RGB values, a challenging inverse problem (Shi et al. 2018; Pan et al. 2023)."
  ]
}